<HEADLINE>
<P>
RECORD LOW TEMPERATURES SNAP HEAT WAVE ACROSS MUCH OF U.S. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Much of the eastern two-thirds of the nation cooled off today after a heat wave 
that toppled temperature records in at least eight states. 
</P>
<P>
The summer break was most apparent for residents in the north-central United 
States, where temperatures early today were generally in the 50s and upper 40s. 
</P>
<P>
In the hours after midnight, several record lows fell for the date, including 
at Kansas City, Mo., 55 degrees; Lincoln, Neb., 50; Marquette, Mich., 41; Des 
Moines, Iowa, 48; Chicago, 52; Topeka, Kan., 49; Milwaukee, 50, and South Bend, 
Ind., 46. 
</P>
<P>
Strong thunderstorms developed Sunday night in east-central New Mexico, Texas, 
northwestern Oklahoma and Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
In Memphis, Tex., nearly two inches of rain fell in 45 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
Early today, the thunderstorms and showers extended from New Mexico into 
Louisiana, with the strongest storms in Texas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
