<P>
N.Y.'S ANGELS GO EN GARDE IN INCREASINGLY DANGEROUS PARIS METRO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PARIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Four members of the Guardian Angels vigilante group descended on the Paris 
Metro today to test their New York style of crime control on this city's 
increasingly dangerous underground system. 
</P>
<P>
"We're here to feel the atmosphere, to see if they need us," Guardian Angel 
co-founder Lisa Sliwa told a press conference at Chatelet, one of the city's 
roughest Metro stations. 
</P>
<P>
A thick belt of photographers and journalists surrounded the Angels, who wore 
the group's trademark red berets. 
</P>
<P>
Travelers were squeezed aside as the Angels passed through the turnstiles and 
took up position on the platform. 
</P>
<P>
Passengers, mostly tourists, looked on in confused amusement. One American 
tourist shouted out, "Yeah, you do a great job in New York, I tell ya, good 
luck!" 
</P>
