<HEADLINE>
<P>
RAIL WORKERS, SANTA FE AGREE TO CUT IN SIZE OF SOME TRAIN CREWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Railroad workers have ratified an agreement with the Santa Fe Railway that 
authorizes a reduction in the size of some freight train crews, the carrier 
announced today. 
</P>
<P>
"This agreement covers 30% of Santa Fe's conductors, trainmen and yardmen," the 
railway said. "None of the approximately 1,300 employees involved will be 
furloughed as a result of this agreement." 
</P>
<P>
A standard crew consists of one conductor, one brakeman and one locomotive 
engineer. Under the agreement, on designated intermodal trains, which represent 
20% of the railway's through trains, there will be no brakeman. 
</P>
<P>
In return, the railway is providing $75,000 to each employee who voluntarily 
resigns. Those remaining employees will receive a $10,000 cash payment to be 
paid by the end of September and $65,000 to be indexed for inflation and 
distributed when they retire or leave the company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
